{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_vrtx_01AESydUvz77isFRk9mjRccE","type":"tool_result","content":"1\t# Vector Databases\n2\t\n3\tA vector database stores data as high-dimensional vectors (embeddings) and enables fast similarity search. They are a key component in [RAG](retrieval-augmented-generation.md) pipelines, recommendation systems, and semantic search.\n4\t\n5\t## Popular Options\n6\t\n7\t- **ChromaDB** — open-source, easy to set up, Python-native\n8\t- **Pinecone** — managed service, scales automatically\n9\t- **Weaviate** — open-source, supports hybrid search (vector + keyword)\n10\t- **Qdrant** — open-source, Rust-based, high performance\n11\t- **pgvector** — PostgreSQL extension; adds vector storage and ANN search to an existing Postgres DB\n12\t\n13\t## How They Work\n14\t\n15\t1. Documents are converted to embeddings using a model\n16\t2. Embeddings are indexed for fast nearest-neighbor search\n17\t3. At query time, the query is embedded and compared to stored vectors\n18\t4. The most similar vectors (and their associated documents) are returned\n19\t\n20\t## Use Cases\n21\t\n22\t- [RAG systems](retrieval-augmented-generation.md) for grounding LLM responses\n23\t- Semantic search across large document collections\n24\t- Recommendation engines\n25\t- Image and audio similarity search\n26\t\n27\t## Related\n28\t\n29\t- [Vector Similarity Search](vector-similarity-search.md) — the algorithms (HNSW, IVF) that power the nearest-neighbor queries vector DBs run\n30\t- [Retrieval-Augmented Generation](retrieval-augmented-generation.md) — primary consumer of vector DB retrieval\n31\t\n32\t## Sources\n33\t\n34\t- sources/vector-databases.md\n35\t- Ingested: 2026-07-09 (updated: added pgvector)\n36\t"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"3eb498bf-647d-4fd5-b1cf-ebc13f299e0f","uuid":"00bf8402-7924-40c1-8e65-0d920b4474a4","timestamp":"2026-07-09T15:56:39.927Z","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/Users/ejaquez/second-brain/wiki/vector-databases.md","content":"# Vector Databases\n\nA vector database stores data as high-dimensional vectors (embeddings) and enables fast similarity search. They are a key component in [RAG](retrieval-augmented-generation.md) pipelines, recommendation systems, and semantic search.\n\n## Popular Options\n\n- **ChromaDB** — open-source, easy to set up, Python-native\n- **Pinecone** — managed service, scales automatically\n- **Weaviate** — open-source, supports hybrid search (vector + keyword)\n- **Qdrant** — open-source, Rust-based, high performance\n- **pgvector** — PostgreSQL extension; adds vector storage and ANN search to an existing Postgres DB\n\n## How They Work\n\n1. Documents are converted to embeddings using a model\n2. Embeddings are indexed for fast nearest-neighbor search\n3. At query time, the query is embedded and compared to stored vectors\n4. The most similar vectors (and their associated documents) are returned\n\n## Use Cases\n\n- [RAG systems](retrieval-augmented-generation.md) for grounding LLM responses\n- Semantic search across large document collections\n- Recommendation engines\n- Image and audio similarity search\n\n## Related\n\n- [Vector Similarity Search](vector-similarity-search.md) — the algorithms (HNSW, IVF) that power the nearest-neighbor queries vector DBs run\n- [Retrieval-Augmented Generation](retrieval-augmented-generation.md) — primary consumer of vector DB retrieval\n\n## Sources\n\n- sources/vector-databases.md\n- Ingested: 2026-07-09 (updated: added pgvector)\n","numLines":36,"startLine":1,"totalLines":36}}}
